<section xml:id="HWDefiningDimension">
  <title>HOMEWORK: Defining Dimension</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
          <idx><h>HOMEWORK: Defining Dimension</h></idx>
      We have now seen the dimension of fractals and of vector spaces.
      Mathematician and author, David Richeson,
      explored the concept of dimension further in amazing Quanta Magazine article:
      <q>The Journey to Define Dimension</q>
      \cite{richeson}.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>The Journey to Define Dimension</title>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Read David Richeson's article
          <q>The Journal to Define Dimension</q>
          from Quanta Magazine.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      \link{https://www.quantamagazine.org/a-mathematicians-guided-tour-through-high-dimensions-20210913/ }
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Describe what we would observe if a 4-dimensional sphere collided with our 3-dimensional space.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          List four people mentioned in this article and their contribution to the discussion of dimension.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Georg Cantor talked about the cardinality of infinity.
          What does he mean by
          <q>cardinality</q>? Explain what Cantor was referring to when he said,
          <q>I see it, but I do not believe it.</q>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How did Hausdorff define dimension?
          What mathematical concept came from his definition?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
